[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, for a long time now, there\'s been this grand concept of having some sort of camera system that is connected to the internet in some way and has access to apps. You know, this ability to take photos, edit them with apps, post them onto social media, share them right'

[00:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'away. And of course, this is a huge benefit. We use this all the time nowadays with smartphones, but there have been many attempts in the past by manufacturers to make photo modules that stick on the front of your phone and give you better image quality and then'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you can use the phone to edit it or even cameras that try to do this in camera. Things like the Samsung Galaxy NX, for example, or the Zeiss ZX1. And unfortunately, a lot of these systems have largely failed. I mean, this is why'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the smartphone is such a powerful and popular tool in the hands of everybody cuz it\'s convenient, but there\'s still the allure of having maybe better manual controls, the ability to change lenses, and get the characteristics of different'

[00:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'glass, and have more natural-looking depth of field. This is something that still alludes a lot of smartphones, and that\'s where camera intelligence comes in because this is the second attempt at a camera that interfaces directly with the smartphone, but gives you a micro'

[01:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '4/3 sensor and the interchangeability of the micro 4/3 lens mount. Now, when this first came out, it\'s no understatement this created a huge storm, and that\'s largely based on how the Kai camera'

[01:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interfaced with AI photographic technology. And I want to talk about the ramifications were of that and where the Kai camera sits now. And I also want to do some of this camera that not a lot of people have done, and that is take it in the field and actually test it because'

[01:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s what we love to do. I\'m Chris Nichols. This is PetaPixel. This is a very interesting camera, and there\'s a lot to talk about. So, to give you guys a little backstory'

[01:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here, when the Kai camera was first announced and then found its way into the hands of a few influencers to get it sort of official first review, this was happening just months after the release of Google\'s brand new nano banana generative AI photo tool. And what this'

[01:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tool basically does is scour the internet, take legitimate artwork, steal it all, and then, you know, you can just generate whatever the hell you want. And I mean, the use of it is dubious. It damages creators and their hard work.'

[02:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'For the most part, photographers are really against this technology, and I think they should be. But, what was unique about the Cyera camera was that it was seamlessly integrating Nano Banana\'s access into its UI interface.'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So, anytime you take photos on the camera, this is important to get across. The camera itself, the photo-taking part is completely separate from any sort of generative AI. I mean, there\'s computational technology here I want to'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'talk about. There\'s neural networks to handle things like better autofocus, white balance. This is something that all cameras do. Nothing wrong with that in my eyes. It then transfers those photos over to your phone, and your phone then works as the separate'

[02:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interface to things like the internet, where you can access things like Nano Banana, for example. And so, look, the idea of this first implementation was that you would have the photos on your phone, you\'d press the button, it would seamlessly connect you to the cloud-based servers for Nano Banana,'

[02:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'upload your photos, and then you could use prompts. You could just speak to the phone and make changes to the photographs or generate all sorts of stuff. And you know, if Camera Intelligence, the company behind Cyera, was hoping that you\'d use this AI tool'

[03:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to do some small enhancements, maybe change the overall feel or color tone, maybe get rid of some distractions, stuff that we do on our smartphone all the time and take for granted, they were sorely mistaken. Because, of course,'

[03:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'what this opened you up for was doing all sorts of crazy AI generation. You can definitely check out some of those early reviews that first came out to see a lot of that. Unfortunately, I think that actually overshadowed the actual concept of the camera entirely, and it'

[03:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'made Camera Intelligence change their entire update structure for how they were going to handle this going forward. Okay, so does this new update on the UI of the Cyera camera still access Nano Banana? Make no mistake, yes, it'

[03:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'absolutely does still access this generative AI tool. But, how it\'s implementing is very different. So, the Cyra camera\'s latest update gets rid of the prompt entirely. That\'s gone. And what Camera Intelligence is doing now is'

[04:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'giving you a series of curated filter effects and looks and changes still using this Nano Banana engine, but not giving you prompt control, you know, to do whatever you want to do with it. And I feel like their goal going forward is'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to keep this more structured. But, does this mean that they could at any moment go back and open the prompt-based AI tool? Yes, absolutely they could. But, this does give us an interesting opportunity to test this camera as it\'s'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'intended to right now. So, as you can see, today we got this beautiful day, and I\'m going to mention the date, although it\'s not something that I normally do, but it\'s actually Good Friday, 2026, and I\'m mentioning that because first off, the Cyra has changed'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'substantially since its announcement, as we\'ve already talked about, and it\'s going to change a lot more going forward. And that\'s kind of part of the nature of this camera that I want to discuss. So, this did originally start as a Kickstarter, and these models are'

[04:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'starting production. They\'re going out to their backers now, and this camera is going to go into full production as it is. And that\'s why we really wanted to take a look at the Cyra now, cuz look, I\'m going to be reviewing this camera'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'today as a production camera, because that\'s what it is. And Camera Intelligence understands that we are reviewing this as a fully reviewable camera right now. But, I cannot still help but feel like, in a lot of ways, this camera is pre-production. There\'s'

[05:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'some things that just don\'t feel finalized. Some things that feel fiddly. Some things with the build. I\'m going to share all these things with you because I think the real key to whether this is going to be the right product for you or not is if you feel you can put trust in'

[05:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this company going forward that they\'re going to update this in interesting and thoughtful ways. They seem to have a very passionate team, and it is a very small team, and so it will take time for this camera to gain its refinement. But,'

[05:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I still want you to understand what this tool is about and whether it\'s right for you. Okay, so we\'re going to leave all that generative icky AI stuff for later. We will get to that, but I do want to evaluate this as a camera attachment tool, adding this micro four thirds'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sensor to your iPhone. And it is important to note, this is only for iPhone users. But I\'m curious about this as a camera cuz I\'ve used these large sensor attachments onto phones before. I\'ve reviewed them and they\'ve always'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'been janky and problematic. So, how does this work? Well, logistically, the first thing I want to get across, this has the 12 megapixel sensor that you would find in the Panasonic GH5S. That sensor is not high resolution, but'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it does have a fast readout, which makes sense for the application that we have here, where it\'s transing your phone quickly using electronic shutter and adding a lot of filters to it. Okay, so this camera itself, how does this'

[06:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'contraption work and attach to everything? Well, first off, let\'s talk about the body. I mean, this is a very straightforward camera. There\'s not a lot on it. This hard aluminum grip, at first, looks very scary, but it\'s actually surprisingly comfortable to hold. I was shocked and amazed. There\'s'

[06:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'also a thumb grip on the back, but that\'s not always functional. I\'ll explain why. You do have a double stage shutter here, so you can half press to focus and then all the way to commit. And actually, it feels quite nice. There\'s also a cold shoe up here, so you'

[06:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can attach like a little light or you can put on mics and stuff like that. On the topic of mics, you will also see a legacy 3.5 mm mic jack, but so far it\'s not really supported. It\'s not really working. Our camera intelligence'

[07:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'suggests that you actually do microphones through the USB-C port, which you\'ll find right here on the side. You\'ve also got your on-off button and you\'ve got your lens release for the lens mount. And that\'s basically it. Now, the USB-C port, this is how you'

[07:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'recharge the internal battery in the camera. This is also how you access the internal storage if you want to download stuff off the camera there. It does not connect to the phone via cable at all. That\'s all going to be done through a'

[07:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Wi-Fi interface. We\'re going to talk about that in a bit. The last thing I want to say though here is how it connects to your phone physically is via MagSafe. Now, the magnet\'s nice and strong, okay? I mean, that\'s a good thing, but as you can see here, it doesn\'t prevent rotation and that\'s'

[07:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really annoying and it\'s fiddly and you kind of have to keep your phone sort of level. Also, I\'ve got the iPhone 17 Pro Max, physically large, which means I can\'t use that thumb hold and all of my important stuff like shooting and you'

[07:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'know, my color filters and all that stuff is here right under my thumb, so I can\'t even really hold it with my thumb like on the grip there. So, that\'s kind of tricky. I got to be honest, a little bit fiddly and it doesn\'t feel'

[08:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'confidence-inspiring. I also want to touch on lenses cuz this is by far one of the most exciting aspects of a piece of equipment like this is getting access to that whole library of Micro Four Thirds lenses and I mean, glass is all about character, it\'s about bokeh, it\'s'

[08:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about depth of field, it\'s about color rendition. I mean all of these things transfer through to the phone and that\'s something you don\'t really appreciate with smartphone cameras and optics on their own. Now, I brought a whole series of lenses. I mean I\'ve got Panasonic,'

[08:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'OM, Olympus. We\'re going to try a whole bunch, but right now I\'ve got the excellent Leica DG Vario-Elmar 12 to 60 mm, one of my favorite lenses, F2.8 to 4. This is auto focusing great so far on the camera, no problems and it\'s also'

[08:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'working with the image stabilization, so potentially these should give you the full functionality of the lens that you put on it. I\'m also happy to report that the Wi-Fi interface between the camera itself and the phone seems to be quite reliable. So far in my testing, I really'

[09:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'haven\'t had any issues with it dropping out. I haven\'t had to retry connections very often to get it connected. It\'s actually been working really well. But, there are some other issues when just shooting around on the street, okay? So, this KAIRA camera has an internal'

[09:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'battery, about 5,000 milliamps, about the same as a smartphone, should last you the entire day. It also has 64 gigs of internal storage, but there\'s no like SD card slot or anything like that. It\'s going to be storing files on the camera'

[09:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'as well as transferring it to your phone\'s gallery. And when it comes to like power saving and how we\'re going to handle this, well, it does have a functionality where you can put it to sleep after like a minute or 15 minutes and you can also set a power off time,'

[09:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'right? Just shut off completely. Uh this is going to be important because the on-off switch takes forever. Not only to turn the camera off, but also on again. So, if I was trying to capture something on the street and the camera\'s'

[09:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'not turned on, forget about it, right? I\'m going to try to kind of just let this go into sleep mode for most of the day so I can activate it quickly and keep shooting rapidly. Okay, so I mean, this is one of the nicest screens I\'ve ever used on a camera. I mean, there\'s'

[10:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'no EVF, unfortunately, but hey, I\'ll forgive her that cuz yeah, the iPhone\'s got a great screen. Um also, I want to talk about the autofocus on here, okay? Cuz right now I\'m focusing on the Calgary Tower behind all of these flags and you do have a single point that you'

[10:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can just move around touchscreen on the phone and it works quite well and it will focus where I want to focus in that regard. So far, there\'s no tracking or continuous autofocus, although that is something that Camera Intelligence says that they are working on for the future.'

[10:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But, I do want to say something very important about your auto auto focusing cuz I\'ve tested it quite a bit now with faces and stuff and the detection\'s not quite great. I mean, there\'s things we take for granted now on smartphones and, you know, cameras like Nikons, Canons, and Sonys where'

[10:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ll get that eye detection right to the eye. Well, this is still bring me back to setting a point on someone\'s face and getting tip of the nose focus or eyelash focus. It just doesn\'t quite have the refinement yet. So, for'

[10:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something like this, a tower behind flags, great. But, for people and moving subjects, it\'s still not quite there. The focusing is basically using a contrast detect system. I can feel it going through steps to try to acquire focus, but to its credit, it\'s'

[11:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'predictable and fairly quick and it\'s quiet. Uh what I do like though is the shutter is very responsive. So, when I take a shot, it fires. Once it\'s got focus, it\'s nice and quick, no delay. I don\'t feel like I\'m missing out on any'

[11:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shots or anything like that. So, I dig that. Now, there are a series of very nice color filters built into this and I want to make this clear. This is not generative AI. This is actually computational photography and neural networks built into the camera doing'

[11:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this. So you actually have some really nice color filters and you know, you got neutral, you got vibrant, you\'ve got sort of a film look, a chrome look, a gold look, a black and white. I mean, these are fun and it\'s got a really nice interface, just a circle and if you push'

[11:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the wheel up or down, you change contrast and then left or right, you change sort of like white balance mildly colder or warmer tone. This actually is very straightforward, very intuitive and actually really effective. Now once I'

[11:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'get that tuned in, the Kyra does also give me a healthy amount of manual exposure and control, but I don\'t always love the implementation. Anyways, the first page that you\'re going to have is going to have your basic manual'

[12:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'functionality. So you actually have manual focus, I can click on this and then slide the slider. I also get aperture control and of course it does read the aperture properly from the lens that\'s mounted. I get shutter speed control and because this is an'

[12:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'electronic shutter, I can go up to some insanely fast speeds to control any sort of excess light. And then I don\'t get ISO, but I get what they\'re calling gain, which is very similar kind of structure. But basically, I can crank this up or down to change the overall'

[12:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'exposure and just like ISO, it will add more noise the higher I go. On top of that, I get distortion, I get saturation, I get color temperature and I get tint. So you actually have a healthy amount of creative control over'

[12:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the color and the contrast of your shots. Now as far as the implementation of this whole control system, there\'s good and there\'s bad, okay? I mean, on the good side, the vertical slider is very straightforward. A lot of people from smartphone experience are going to'

[13:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understand how a vertical slider works to make things brighter or darker, for example. Then to actually change settings from automatic to manual, you double click on it. So if I click once on the aperture, it goes red, that means I\'m in manual control. If I click it'

[13:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'again, it goes green and that\'s back into automatic. I will say though that the touch controls in general are a little bit fiddly, like I often have to press things two or sometimes even three times to get them to register. If I\'m taking my time casually, it\'s no big'

[13:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'deal, but if I was trying to grab a shot quickly, it would be very stressful and kind of unreliable. On top of that, I do get manual control of shutter, aperture, and gain, but I don\'t have any sort of exposure compensation. So, I can take a'

[13:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look at a shot and say, "I want that darker than the uh you know, what the meter suggests or brighter than what the meter suggests." And there\'s no way to do that. Even if I take one of these controls out of manual, say aperture for'

[13:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'example, it\'s still automatically going to match everything with the other settings. So, the only way to override the meter is to actually turn everything to full manual and do it myself in a very old-school way. I don\'t really have'

[14:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'an issue with that, but I could see a lot of beginners finding that quite frustrating or confusing. I just got to talk about this again because I\'ve been playing with it here. I mean, the manual focus implementation is awesome. Like, that little split prism rangefinder, and then I can push'

[14:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'halfway and have it magnify as well. This is what the Leica MEV1 should have implemented on its screen. Would have been awesome, but it works great here. One thing that doesn\'t work great though is hot swapping lenses. Hot swapping\'s great in a polyamorous relationship, but'

[14:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s not great on this camera. It\'s a bug. I you know, and they\'re working on fixing that, but if I swap lenses, sometimes it kicks into a different option, doesn\'t let me go back to autofocus. That\'s kind of annoying. And so, there\'s a lot of actual bugs here in'

[14:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this OS that we just kind of got to tough through right now, and hopefully they fix it in the future. So, I want to get this low angle shot, but I\'m like straining my neck to see the screen cuz it doesn\'t rotate, but actually Oh, wait'

[14:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a minute. Oh. There you go. Perfect. Yeah, absolutely. So, I can just attach this. The MagSafe doesn\'t have anything to do with connectivity other than the physical locking of the two together. I can take this off, and'

[15:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this would be really cool for selfie shots, for low angles where I can just like, you know, comfortably see my frame. Oh, that\'s great. And I can just Ooh. A little disorienting, but I I have to remember not to move the phone. It\'s'

[15:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the camera that does it all, but that\'s actually really nice feature. I could see that being useful in a studio situation or product photography setup. So, yeah, that\'s a nice option. All right. So, here\'s a perfect example of where something like this shines'

[15:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'compared to a smartphone, okay? Because I want to use this little 12 mm Panasonic lens, which is working great. Get my focus. Purposefully crank down the aperture to F16, the tightest, and get'

[15:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a really nice sun star. And that\'s something I can\'t do on a phone. I mean, I have to actually ironically go into like AI generative and ask for a sun star or something, right? Like So, this is nice that I can do it optically with the lens, and that is kind of the'

[15:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'benefit here is getting to use actual glass. Woohoohoo! Woo! It\'s just too bright again. I mean, I don\'t like the way it exposes, so I\'m'

[16:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'constantly going in and and setting everything to manual and uh darkening things down a little bit with a faster shutter speed to get some more contrast and depth to the color. But it\'s just fiddly. It\'s not It\'s not'

[16:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fun. It\'s fiddly, and the touchscreen interface isn\'t that responsive, so that just exacerbates the issue. So, I mentioned earlier that this uses the GH5S\'s sensor. Now, this is a 12-megapixel multi-aspect ratio 4/3 sensor. And this actually does some'

[16:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interesting stuff here on this. Not only does it have a faster read speed, which we\'ve talked about, but it does give you different aspect ratios you can shoot while still retaining pretty good detail. So, this will actually do a 17:9 cinematic ultra-widescreen, giving you'

[16:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'about 8.8 megapixels. You can do a 4:3 aspect ratio, just over 10 megapixels. And then if you do 3:2 aspect ratio, that gives you your highest at 11 megapixels. The UI does warn that if you shoot 3:2'

[17:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'ratio, you might get a little bit of vignetting and stuff with some lenses, but so far I haven\'t seen that to be a problem. We also have some pretty nice photo formats here that we can record in. So, I\'ve got JPEGs, of course, and these will actually embed in HDR'

[17:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'profile. So, when I put these on my smartphone, on an HDR screen, I can get it to map that and actually give me that extra dynamic range. Uh another cool thing is DNGs. This shoots both DNGs or DNG Plus, which is their compressed DNG.'

[17:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is lossless. It will take a little bit more time if you\'re processing files in the UI, but it does save space, and that is important. Now, there is 64 gigs of internal storage. Your photos go there, your JPEGs and RAWs. It\'ll also'

[17:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'send that to the phone, and it\'ll show up in your iPhone gallery. So, I got my JPEGs and RAWs in there, as well. So, all in all, it\'s quite convenient. So, we\'ve had a nice day. We\'ve been wandering around for about 3 hours or so now. Battery life, first off, this was'

[17:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fully charged when I left the house, and I have been leaving it pretty much on the whole time, cuz the on-off time, again, is killer. And I\'m down to about 51%. So, I can still shoot quite a few more photos, but it\'s not like I took'

[18:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hundreds today. From a shooting standpoint, from a comfort level, it is kind of an awkward device to use. I mean, I\'m not going to lie, guys. Like, sticking this on here and shooting, I can\'t really hold it as comfortably as I\'d like. I\'ve got the strap, but it\'s'

[18:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all sort of dangling. To its credit, my phone hasn\'t fallen on the ground yet. I thought it would, but this is actually kind of a chunky tool, right? I mean, the convenience of a smartphone is completely gone when you jam this on'

[18:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here. And now we\'re talking about interchangeable lenses, and it feels far more like a system camera, just a kind of awkward one to hold and use. It\'s got a fair bit of weight to it, as well. But, we got some samples. I think we\'re going to head home now. We\'re going to'

[18:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'take a look at it, and yes, we are going to talk about all the dreaded AI stuff that we do with afterwards. All right, so we\'ve gotten into the studio. Let\'s talk about the Nano Banana AI features that we have in this phone, which are largely toned down from what'

[18:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we had before. Okay, so one of the generative AI features that I do want to test out is the studio background generative fill. And I do think this is a legitimate use case where this product will be very useful. If you\'re a small'

[19:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'business owner, let\'s say hypothetically, your boss at the fly shop says, "Chris, you need to sell this Mykus Bay Real VR Design Vladimir Redchenko beautifully made in the Ukraine." And you\'re like, "Okay, well, I don\'t have a studio setup." First thing you do need is a proper light. You'

[19:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can\'t get around that because the AI is not going to touch the subject. It\'s got to look good. So, I\'m using my Westcott L120B continuous light, plenty of power through this 2 by 3 foot rapid box switch, and this is going to give me'

[19:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that nice soft light and really show off that silver detailing. But, look at my background. I got an exercise bike. There\'s yoga stuff in the background, and I\'m putting this on top of a fireplace. I mean, this is not a professional setup, but I can take it'

[19:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here on the shot. I can run it through the AI, and what it\'s going to do is that. Look, I\'m balancing this with a rock. A damn rock is holding this reel up in place, and it totally gets rid of that, puts a nice counter shadow on the'

[20:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'bottom there, and this is now fit for selling on a website. This is a very nice use case. So, you have to have the right light. The Westcott L120B, I love it for any sort of studio work. It\'s got great clean color and nice soft light.'

[20:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You can find this at fjwestcott.com, or click the link in the description below to get the same setup for yourself. That is why we love Westcott. They\'re PetaPixel\'s preferred lighting gear partner. So, that actually worked quite well, and I could see a legitimate use'

[20:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'case where that would be very useful for a small business owner. Now, the other ones that are integrated here that are also pretty extreme, and we call them transformations. Removing clutter in the background. I mean, this is always effective. We\'ve seen this in lots of'

[20:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other smartphones. And honestly, I don\'t have a problem with that because that\'s something that I would do in Lightroom myself. Uh the other one that\'s kind of strange is redirecting somebody\'s eyes towards the camera if they\'re looking away. Now, we tested it here. It does'

[20:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work pretty well, but there\'s like uncanny valley going on. There\'s just something funny about the eyes there, but you may or may not find that useful. Largely, the other modes are going to be like lens effects and color filter'

[21:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effects. And some of them are actually kind of fun, like adding anamorphic flares pretty neat, you know, making things wider angle or fish eye, that\'s pretty generative. I don\'t know if I love that, but then some of the color filters can be very nice. Now, golden'

[21:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hour is an interesting example because that\'s something I could use quite often. I took a shot of this guy sitting down just enjoying a smoke and I love the golden hour effect. It\'s lighting his hair from behind, giving me that rim'

[21:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'light, nice soft light with directionality. I thought it did a great job. But then Jordan tried to test with his son here and it put hard shadows across his face and that wasn\'t really nice. Now, there\'s no way to tone these'

[21:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'effects down or change like opacity or do another generation right away, you know, pick from the top three. You can absolutely just cancel out and try to generate it again and it will do'

[21:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something slightly different and you can go through that process, but one of the major downsides that I have to say with this whole thing now, especially compared to a smartphone that has AI tools, is that this is painfully slow. I'

[22:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mean, slow enough that it takes the fun out of it. Sometimes I\'m waiting 30, 40, 50 seconds and it\'s just not doing it and that\'s that\'s pretty inconvenient. Now, I should also point out that the resolution on these is fairly low. I'

[22:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'mean, you can do the 2K resolution, that\'s where it takes the most time to generate. That\'s just over 4 megapixels. You can have that to 1K and you basically have those megapixels and you\'ll have the time it takes to generate the files, but again, you know,'

[22:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like the resolution\'s not going to be great for anything except maybe social media usage. And that brings me to my next thing is like, look, I\'m no fan of the prompt-based AI tool, right? I really didn\'t like what that stands for. I don\'t like what it does ethically to'

[22:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'photography, but I will say that this new revision, this pullback, as it were, feels a lot like just fun collective filter effects and it doesn\'t really feel like much more than that, you know? I mean, doing things like 1960s 35 mm'

[22:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'film, it\'s going to drop saturation, you\'re going to get an analog frame and a color overlay. Like that\'s not super generative stuff, which uh maybe is part of the solution, right? If people are pushing back so hard on the AI'

[23:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'generation, maybe this gives you more of a curated toned-down kind of approach. At the same time though, it\'s kind of weird because I feel like now I\'m missing out on some of the more powerful applications or be able to take creative'

[23:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'control to use Nano Banana in ways that I might find more interesting. The only other thing that\'s worth noting in the sort of AI generative module is the assistant tool. And this will basically just look at your photograph and then it'

[23:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'makes some suggestions about how you could compose this differently. We\'ve seen this in other things as well. A lot of smartphones have this too. And it it\'ll just say, "Oh, maybe next time you should go lower, or maybe try changing the colors." And I\'m like, it\'s not going to do any sort of generative AI to your photo. It\'s just going to make'

[23:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these suggestions. And what is interesting is when you go into the info on your photos, you can not only see all the suggestions that the assistant made, so you can I guess learn from them for future use, but it will also show you all of the AI generative stuff that was'

[23:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'added to the photograph as well. So it kind of keeps track of all the things that you\'ve done to it. So this brings me to a bit of an AI conundrum, and I want to talk about this later on. So I let let\'s just keep going on here while we\'re talking about image quality and get into some of the computational'

[24:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'photographic effects that have been added very recently to this version of the Kyra. Because this stuff is quite compelling. So we\'ve long talked about how computational photo effects where you\'re stacking multiple images and doing'

[24:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'beneficial things with them is a great tool. We love this in a lot of Micro Four Thirds camera. Olympus {slash} OM System would of course be the one that\'s most advanced in this. I love their Live ND tools and you know, the ability to'

[24:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'add resolution and stuff like that. And Panasonic has also been doing this in a lot of their cameras. And by stacking these multiple images, we can up the resolution. We can reduce noise. We can increase dynamic range. These are all'

[24:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'great things. And this is all powerful stuff that we appreciate in every smartphone that we own as well. Stacking of images is a really cool tool, and I wish we would see more cameras do it. So, when we found out that the Kyra does'

[24:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'do this in one of its modes, it was very compelling. I do have to point out though that the computational effects on this camera are definitely in their infancy. So, what Camera Intelligence is doing on the Kyra is offering a brand new feature called low light. Now,'

[25:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'ve got your photo mode, your video mode, and now low light. And when you engage low light, it can stack frames. It can stack up to 16 shots. And it\'s going to decide a lot of stuff in this mode. You can\'t choose your exposure'

[25:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'really. You can\'t choose how many shots to stack. It will kind of figure that all out intelligently based on the scene and the overall dynamic range and how low the light levels are. But, what is cool is it will show you how many files'

[25:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it stacked. Even shows you a buffer so you can see when it still has room to make stacks. And if you shoot too quickly, you might have to then slow down and wait for it to build up a little bit and clear off before you can do some more.'

[25:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'What we\'re seeing with the results though isn\'t huge, but it is there. So, in the low light mode when you see the stack shots, we definitely get less noise. But, we also tend to get a little bit less detail. Things tend to be a little bit softer. That might just be'

[25:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'based on how it\'s melding all of those images together. I\'m not quite sure on that, but we\'re definitely noticing a little loss of detail, but cleaner shots. So, it\'s kind of a trade-off right now. We expect to see this get better though going down the road. And'

[26:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'uh Camera Intelligence has also said that they\'re absolutely dedicated to raising the megapixel count. Going from 11 megapixels up to like 44 megapixels, for example, doing some stacked high-res shots. Again, we\'ve seen this technology'

[26:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'before. It does work well and so I imagine we\'ll get similar results from here when they implement it. This is what I will say about the whole Kyra experience when it comes to image quality. Uh I mean, I\'m still enjoying the Micro Four Thirds dynamic range. I can push'

[26:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and pull these files. I like the images that I got out of this. I like being able to see the quality and characteristics of the lenses that I\'m choosing to use in the files. And I also will say that I think Camera Intelligence has done a a job with their'

[26:48] [scene:talk]
